235–Overleden","1237–Female":"1237–Overleden","1237":"1237","1235":"1235","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1260–1295":"1260–1295","1260–Female":"1260–Deceased","1280–1320":"1280–1320","1235–Male":"1235–Deceased","1237–Female":"1237–Deceased","1237":"1237","1235":"1235","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ackworth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Ackworth (WR Yorks), which is recorded as  <i>Aceuurde</i> in 1086,  <i>Akeworth</i> in 1201, and  <i>Akworthe</i> in the 14th century. The place-name means ‘Acca's enclosure’, from the Old English personal name  <i>Acca</i> +  <i>worð</i> ‘enclosure, curtilage’."],"variants":[{"name":"Acworth","meanings":["English:  see  Ackworth  ."]},{"name":"Hackworth","meanings":["English (Durham and Northumberland): variant of <b>Ackworth</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a habitational name from Ackworth (Yorkshire). The placename means ‘Acca's enclosure’, from the Old English personal name <i>Acca</i> + <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure, curtilage’."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When George Ackworth was born in 1260, in Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, Ackworth or Ashworth, was 26 and his mother, Ackworth, was 24. He married Elizabeth Horne. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1295, in Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1260–1295":"1260–1295","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1280–1320":"1280–1320","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1237–Female":"1237–Surnud","1237":"1237","1235":"1235","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1260–1295":"1260–1295","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1280–1320":"1280–1320","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","1237–Female":"1237–Kuollut","1237":"1237","1235":"1235","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1260–1295":"1260–1295","1260–Female":"1260–Décédée","1280–1320":"1280–1320","1235–Male":"1235–Décédé","1237–Female":"1237–Décédée","1237":"1237","1235":"1235","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","England":"Angleterre","Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque George Ackworth est né en 1260, à Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Ackworth or Ashworth, avait 26 ans et sa mère, Ackworth, avait 24 ans. Il a épousé Elizabeth Horne. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Il es